      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "From a strict global human rights perspective, the asylum argument carries a stronger intrinsic moral weight because it centers on the inherent dignity and right to life of the individual. The concept of borders, while politically real, is a construct that can be secondary to fundamental human needs. Therefore, if your debate leans toward international law and universal ethics, the humanitarian position has the stronger foundational claim. However, you must acknowledge the real-world security concerns that underpin the opposition's view to make your argument robust.",
      "source": "target",
